==Latin==

===Etymology===
From {{proto|Indo-European|ad-|to, near, at|lang=la}}. Cognates include English {{term|at||lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
<span id="Latin#Pronunciation"/>
* {{IPA|/ad/|lang=la}}

===Preposition===
{{infl|la|preposition}} (+ {{accusative}})

# {{context|direction}} [[toward]], [[to]], [[up to]]
#: '''''Ad''' vim atque [[ad arma|'''ad''' arma]] confugere.''
#:: To fly '''to''' violence and '''to''' fighting.
#* ''[[w:Lucretius|Lucretius]]'', from the fourth book of ''[[w:De Rerum Natura|De Rerum Natura]]''
#*: ''Fugere '''ad''' puppim colles campique videntur.''
#*:: The hills and fields appear to fly '''toward''' the ship.
#* ''[[w:Pliny the Elder|Pliny the Elder]]'', from book II of ''[[w:Naturalis Historia|Naturalis Historia]]''
#*: ''Meridie umbrae cadunt '''ad''' septentrionem, ortu vero '''ad''' occasum.''
#*:: At noon the shadows fall '''towards''' the north, [and] at sunrise, point '''to''' the west.
#* ''[[w:Aeneid|Aeneid]]'' by ''[[w:Virgil|P. Vergilius Maro]]''
#*: ''Duplices tendens '''ad''' sidera palmas.''
#*:: Stretching both hands '''to''' the stars.

====Related terms====
* [[ad-]] (same word modified and used as a prefix)

====Usage notes====
* The word '''ad''' is an [[antithesis]] to {{term|ab|lang=la}} (just as {{term|in|lang=la}} is to {{term|ex|lang=la}}; in a progressive order of relation, {{term|ad|lang=la}} denotes, first, the direction toward an object; then the reaching of or attaining to it; and finally, the being at or near it.)
* Often used of geographical position of a place in reference to the points of compass, with the verbs {{term|iaceo|iaceō|lie, be situated|lang=la}}, {{term|vergo|vergō|incline, slope|lang=la}}, {{term|specto|spectō|observe, see|lang=la}} etc.:
*: ''Asia iacet '''ad''' meridiem et austrum, Europa '''ad''' septentriones et aquilonem.''
*:: Asia lies '''near''' the prime meridian and the south, Europe '''near''' the northern regions and northern wind. (two words for north)
*: '''''Ad''' Atticam vergente.''
*:: Inclining '''to''' Attic.

